english:
  title: In Response to Dongmungong, the Recording Clerk
  author: Lim Yujeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the study hall, day after day brings no urgent matters—Han Yu knows this well.
    I lie drowsing, seeking sleep while still turning pages—Yongseok's way.
    I rinse the cups and open vessels of fresh wine—as Du Fu did.
    I call the servants to sweep the old house clean—following Sima Guang.
    Delicate flowers lean askew, adorning every branch—Du Fu's vision.
    The cool moon shines cunningly across the courtyard—Lin Min perceives it so.
    In the empty room, dust-laden thoughts dissolve—Tao Qian's refuge.
    Yet Baiju's words prove true and never hollow—his wisdom endures.
  footnotes:
    - This poem employs a classical technique of weaving together fragments from celebrated poets and historical figures, creating a tapestry of contemplative life and refined leisure.
    - The progression moves from intellectual pursuits (reading, wine) through domestic order (sweeping) to spiritual emptiness (the empty room), reflecting a journey toward inner peace.
    - Tao Qian and Bai Juyi (Baiju) represent different philosophical approaches to contentment—one through withdrawal, the other through acceptance.
